Verb handlers are a middleware sub-stack:

https://expressjs.com/en/guide/using-middleware.html#middleware.router

&gt; Router-level middleware works in the same way as application-level middleware, except it is bound to an instance of express.Router().

A specific example from that link:

    // a middleware sub-stack that handles GET requests to the /user/:id path
    router.get(&#39;/user/:id&#39;, function (req, res, next) {
      // Etc.
    }

Verb middleware doesn&#39;t always look like &quot;generic&quot; middleware because it&#39;s often the end of a middleware chain, but ultimately it&#39;s the same thing.

Contrast typical verb handlers with middleware executed for every request:

    // a middleware function with no mount path. This code is executed for every request to the router
    router.use(function (req, res, next) {
      console.log(&#39;Time:&#39;, Date.now())
      next()
    })

Think of middleware as an &quot;interceptor&quot;, with verb middlewares as a somewhat pathological case in that they very often just ignore `next` since they&#39;re typically responsible for sending the response and nothing else&amp;ndash;but they *can* still continue processing.

